When former OpenAI researcher Leopold Aschenbrenner published this series, it felt like someone finally put numbers behind the whispers I kept hearing out of San Francisco. His argument is simple but staggering. Stacking order-of-magnitude compute scaling alongside algorithmic efficiency and agentic unhobbling makes AGI by 2027 look like a reasonable baseline projection.

What makes his perspective so jarring is how grounded it is in hardware realities. He tracks boardroom plans jumping from $10 billion clusters to trillion-dollar buildouts, requiring unprecedented expansion of electrical power grids and supply chains. Even if you stretch his timeline by a few years or remain skeptical about an automated intelligence explosion, his core thesis holds up. The primary bottlenecks for frontier AI have moved beyond raw algorithm design to physical infrastructure, industrial capacity, and national security.

### What stuck with me

* **The counting OOMs model:** Progress isn't just GPU scaling; algorithmic efficiency gains deliver roughly as much performance gain per year as hardware growth.
* **The power wall:** Scaling to million-GPU clusters by 2028 requires adding tens of percent to total US electricity production, turning AI into an energy industrial challenge.
* **Lab security as national defense:** Model weights and cluster blueprints are already prime targets for state actors, making cybersecurity at leading AI labs a critical national vulnerability.
* **Automated AI research:** Once models reach human-level AI research capabilities, the feedback loop could compress a decade of research into months.
